<DOC><DOCNO> AP880812-0151 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1934EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--RailStrike     08-12 0134</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Rail Strike,0139</SECOND><HEAD>Railway Workers Demonstrate To Demand Better Pay</HEAD><DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   About 400 uniformed workers from thestate-run railway marched through the streets Friday to demandhigher wages and overtime pay.   The workers from Taiwan Railway Administration handed a petitionto Communications Ministry officials.   A spokesman for the workers, Yang Ching-chang, said the railwaycompany should raise their salaries and immediately make overtimepayments owed to the workers. The workers did not say how much morethey want.   After a one-day strike by conductors in May that halted railservice throughout the island, the railway had promised to make theovertime payments over a four-year period.   Railway workers earn an average of about $700 a month.   Taiwan legalized strikes in June but banned strikes without theauthorization of labor associations.</TEXT></DOC>